<HEADLINE> Indian, Pakistani Leaders Exchange Olive Branch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MALE, the Maldives, May 12 (Xinhua) -- Indian Prime Minister
Inder Kumar Gujral said here today that his country heartily
endorses Pakistan's initiative to hold bilateral talks with India
at various levels.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a speech at the inauguration of the ninth SAARC
(South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation) summit just
before his face-to-face meeting with his Pakistani counterpart
Nawaz Sharif, Gujral said the recent convincing mandate enjoyed by
Nawaz Sharif in Pakistan helped usher in a new era.
</P>
<P>
"This has been a cause of encouragement for India," he said.
"We are also encouraged that Nawaz Sharif has committed to the
process of dialog to normalize relations with India."
</P>
<P>
"Today's meeting will add another milestone in further
enhancing the cooperation and good-neighborly relations between
the two countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I value my friendship with Nawaz Sharif and I hope it will
open a new era in our bilateral relations and SAARC cooperation,"
he added. "I welcome Nawaz Sharif's statement."
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the opening session of the SAARC summit,
Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said Pakistan is determined
to continue the process of dialog with India "so that all
outstanding issues can be comprehensively addressed".
</P>
<P>
"With sincerity and resolve we can overcome these problems and
establish good neighborly and cooperative relations," he said.
"The dividends of success will be enormous not only for Pakistan
and India but also for the entire SAARC region."
</P>
<P>
Gujral and Sharif are expected to hold a face-to-face meeting
over lunch on Kurumba Resort Island, the first meeting between the
prime ministers of the two countries since April 1993, when Nawaz
Sharif and then Indian prime minister Narasimha Rao met also on
the sidelines of a SAARC summit in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri
Lanka and the Maldives.  
</P>
